In article <NICKH.94May9095124@abel.harlqn.co.uk>,
>- Breaking RSA129 consisted of factoring a 129-digit number (i.e.
>about 430 bits) into its two large prime factors. This is the
>brute-force approach (*) to breaking any RSA coding. It does not
>involve "factoring very large primes", as Kurt repeatedly suggests
>(what is this phrase even supposed to mean?)
[...]
>(*) the only approach known; other approaches have not yet been
>theoretically ruled out.

Picking a nit here: the "brute-force approach to breaking any
RSA coding" involves trying each possible private key to see
if it works; i.e. trying an estimated 1/2 * 10^129 keys, on
average.  Factoring the modulus is the best of the known
attacks on RSA, but not the only possible attack known.

		--Ken Pizzini
